<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911118-0024</DOCNO><DOCID>911118-0024.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Ex-Lamar Savings   Chief Adams Pleads   Guilty to Bank Fraud</HL><DATE>11/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7</SO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   AUSTIN, Texas -- Former thrift Chairman Stanley E. AdamsJr., who once tried to outfly his high-flying Texas brethrenby applying to open a thrift branch on the moon, pleadedguilty to federal fraud charges.   The guilty plea Friday ended a long-running criminalinvestigation into the failure of Lamar Savings Associationof Austin, which collapsed in 1985 with $2 billion in assets.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Adams, who made an unsuccessful bid for the Democraticnomination for Texas governor while under investigation,pleaded guilty to conspiring to hide Lamar's worseningfinancial condition by issuing sham loans to borrowers whopurportedly were buying repossessed real estate from thethrift.   Mr. Adams also pleaded guilty to falsely recording salesproceeds and loan fees in Lamar's books in connection with a$15.7 million loan.   A sentencing date and possible prison term weren'timmediately available. Mr. Adams and his wife, a shareholderin the company, had already agreed to pay the government $1.9million to settle a civil lawsuit over the failure of LamarSavings.   Mr. Adams is the fifth person to plead guilty or beconvicted of charges related to Lamar's loans. Two thriftofficers were convicted of conspiracy and misapplication ofthrift funds after a trial last month. Earlier this year,Dallas real estate developer Louis G. Reese III pleadedguilty to fraud in connection with money he borrowed fromLamar Savings. Another borrower, Vijay Parekh, was convictedlast year of charges related to a fraudulent loan.</TEXT></DOC>